LECTURE: In an assignment, an object is assigned to a variable. In Java, you can assign an object to a variable by placing the variable's name before the assignment operator, and then placing the object's name after the assignment operator. For example:
String s = "Hello, World!";
assigns the string "Hello, World!" to the variable s.

You can have multiple variables assigned to the same object. For example:
String s1 = "Hello, World!";
String s2 = "Hello, World!";
Now, both s1 and s2 are assigned to the same object.

If you want to swap the objects assigned to two variables, you can use the following code:
// Java
s1 = s2;
s2 = s;
//
// C++
s1 = s2;
s2 = s;
//
// C#
s1 = s2;
s2 = s;
//
// Python
s1 = s2;
s2 = s;
//
// JavaScript
s1 = s2;
s2 = s;
//
ANSWER: D.
